(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-38-calculating-horizontal-floor-length-ruffles-with-arbitrarily-chosen-intervals-between-sewing-lines/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-38-calculating-horizontal-floor-length-ruffles-with-arbitrarily-chosen-intervals-between-sewing-lines/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:43:42+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T18:43:42+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 38. Calculating Horizontal Floor-Length Ruffles with Arbitrarily Chosen Intervals between Sewing Lines."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 38. Calculating Horizontal Floor-Length Ruffles with Arbitrarily Chosen Intervals between Sewing Lines."><meta itemprop="description" content="Calculating Horizontal Floor-Length Ruffles tables to define fabric consumption for the highly popular elastic waist skirt"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 38. Calculating Horizontal Floor-Length Ruffles with Arbitrarily Chosen Intervals between Sewing Lines.</h1><p>Before I start explaining how to use my automatic calculation tables to define fabric consumption for the highly popular elastic waist skirt, <strong>I want to teach you how to use them to calculate length parameters and fabric consumption for horizontal ruffles of a petticoat or a fabric casing when they are placed at different levels but all reach down to the floor. </strong>The shape of the skirt itself does not matter here: it can be a full-circle skirt, a half-circle skirt, or a skirt cut with any desired sector angle. The calculation method will stay the same.</p><p><strong>First of all, sketch your petticoat or fabric casing on a piece of paper and write down all initial parameters. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The drawing above is a fabric petticoat casing with three horizontal ruffles, a waist circumference of 75cm, and a length of 105cm. </strong></p><p>The top ruffle (1) goes 45cm below waistline, the second ruffle (2) – 65cm below waistline, and the third ruffle (3) – 85cm below waistline.</p><p>There are 20cm intervals between the sewing lines.</p><p>All ruffles reach down to the floor, i.e. their bottom edges are positioned at the same level as the hem of the face skirt with a length of 120cm. And therefore, ruffle (1) is 75cm long, ruffle (2) – 55cm long, and ruffle (3) – 35cm long.</p><p><strong>Here is how we calculate fabric consumption for these ruffles using the automatic calculation tables. </strong></p><p>First you choose an automatic calculation table corresponding with the shape of your skirt. Then you determine sewing line lengths for all three ruffles following the previously described technique. And, finally, you calculate fabric consumption for the ruffles as for three separate skirts by putting the ruffle sewing edge length in the table under <em>Waist Circumference</em> and the length of the corresponding ruffle under <em>Skirt Length</em>. To put it more simply, we sort of remove the top part of the skirt from the waistline down to the beginning of the ruffle and calculate all parameters for the ruffle as if it were a short skirt. And, of course, you must remember to account for a certain gathering ratio at the joint.</p><p>This makes my automatic calculation tables flexible enough to allow you to calculate any kinds of ruffles for skirts of any shapes with or without train.</p><p><strong>The key thing </strong>is to be very attentive, draw a similar ruffles layout for yourself, and write as many initial parameters as possible on it. This will help you avoid mistakes in the calculations.</p><p><strong>So, let us begin. We will use an automatic calculation table to calculate horizontal floor-length ruffles for a half-circle skirt in our case. </strong></p><p><strong>Open the Table for Calculating a Half-Circle Skirt and go to the Horizontal Ruffles tab. </strong></p><p><strong>We will start from calculating the bottom edge lengths of the three ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>Ruffle 1.</strong> Imagine that we are doing calculations for a skirt with a waist circumference of 75cm and a length of 45cm. The ruffle sewing line is positioned 45cm below waistline on our drawing.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I fill in the initial parameters: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 75cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 45cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length – 45cm. There is no train.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>We only need one calculated parameter: </strong></p><p><strong>- Total Hem Length – 220cm.</strong> I write it down on the writing board.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 2.</strong> Imagine that we are now doing calculations for a skirt with a waist circumference of 75cm and a length of 65cm. The corresponding sewing line is positioned 65cm below waistline on the drawing.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I fill in the initial parameters for calculations: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 75cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 65cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length – 65cm. There is no train.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>We need only one calculated parameter: </strong></p><p><strong>- Total Hem Length – 280cm.</strong> I write it down on the writing board.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 3.</strong> Now imagine that we are doing calculations for a skirt with a waist circumference of 75cm and a length of 85cm. The corresponding sewing line is positioned 85cm below waistline on the drawing.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us fill in the initial parameters: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 75cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 85cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length – 85cm. There is no train.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>We are only interested in one calculated parameter: </strong></p><p><strong>- Total Hem Length – 340cm.</strong> I write it down on the writing board.</p><p><strong>Now we can start calculating fabric consumption for our ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>Ruffle 1.</strong> Imagine as if this ruffle were going to be put along the top edge of some skirt with a waist circumference equal to the length of the calculated ruffle sewing line (220cm) and a length equal to the ruffle length (75cm). I will cut this ruffle from 300cm-wide tulle, just as an example, and gather it to 1/6<sup>th</sup> of the original length.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us fill in the initial parameters (<em>Key Skirt Parameters</em>):</strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 220cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 75cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length – 75cm. There is no train.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>And we add more parameters (<em>Key Parameters of Horizontal Skirt Ruffles</em>): </strong></p><p>- Number of Ruffles – 1,</p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio – 6,</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 300cm.</p><p><strong>We only need one calculated parameter: </strong></p><p><strong>- Ruffle Fabric Consumption – 310cm.</strong> I write it down on our drawing.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 2.</strong></p><p>Imagine as if this ruffle were going to put along the top edge of some skirt with a waist circumference equal to the length of the calculated ruffle sewing line (280cm) and a length equal to the ruffle length (55cm).</p><p>I will use 150cm-wide mesh fabric of medium density for this ruffle and gather it to 1/3<sup>rd</sup> of the original length (i.e. use a gathering ratio of 3).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I fill in the initial parameters (<em>Key Skirt </em>Parameters): </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 280cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 55cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length – 55cm. There is no train.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>And I fill in more parameters (<em>Key Parameters of Horizontal Skirt </em>Ruffles):</strong></p><p>- Number of Ruffles – 1,</p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio – 3,</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 150cm.</p><p><strong>Again, we only need one calculated parameter: </strong></p><p><strong>- Ruffle Fabric Consumption – 340cm.</strong> I write it down on the writing board.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 3.</strong></p><p>Now imagine as if the ruffle were going to be put along a skirt with a waist circumference equal to the length of the calculated ruffle sewing line (340cm) and a length equal to the ruffle length (35cm).</p><p>I will cut this ruffle from 120cm-wide mesh fabric of high density, just as an example, and gather it to ½ of the original length.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I fill in the key skirt parameters: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 340cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 35cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length – 35cm. There is no train.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>And I fill in the key parameters of horizontal ruffles:</strong></p><p>- Number of Ruffles – 1,</p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio – 2,</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 120cm.</p><p><strong>We only need one calculated parameter:</strong></p><p><strong>- Ruffle Fabric Consumption – 220cm.</strong> I write it down on the writing board.</p><p><strong>Now we know how much fabric we need for each of the three ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>The results of all calculations are written on the writing board. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2038.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I think I have managed to show you </strong>that calculating fabric consumption and lengths of various ruffles and flounces can turn into quite an agreeable pastime as soon as you learn how to use my automatic calculation tables.</p><p>And, of course, you can follow the same method to calculate ruffles of varied widths put on the garment at various unequal intervals. It is another great advantage of these tables. All you need is to understand how they work.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>A